icated technology. For D: responds to unexpected events adequately, can concentrate very well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously, regarded as a know-it-all, has a hot temper. Also earlier mention: D is regarded as a know-it-all (maybe arrogance). Also D has hot temper (negative). For A: anticipate dangerous situations, see complex connections, excellent spatial vision, very good leadership qualities, regarded as a show-off, not open to new ideas.\n\nWe need to evaluate for long-distance pilot: reliability, technical competence, calm under pressure, decision-making, teamwork, professional development.\n\nWe have explicit calmness for B (keeps calm in a crisis). For D we have \"responds to unexpected events adequately\" but not explicit calmness. For A no calmness. For C no calmness.\n\nWe might ask other agents about B's teamwork (makes nasty remarks) or about C's calmness, D's calmness, etc. But we already have B's calmness. We might ask about B's teamwork/communication, as nasty remarks indicate poor teamwork. Also ask about C's calmness under pressure? Not present. Could ask about D's calmness under pressure. Already asked Agent1, got no info. Could ask Agent3 about D's calmness? Might not have. Could ask about B's reliability? Already known 100% reliable. Could ask about B's memory for numbers (weak) - could affect navigation. Could ask about C's decision speed (good) but communication issues. Could ask about D's hot temper (negative for teamwork). Could ask about A's openness to new ideas (negative). So we have enough to weigh.\n\nWe need to produce public message summarizing assessment and maybe ask targeted question to fill gaps: e.g., ask Agent1 about Candidate B's teamwork/communication, or about Candidate C's calmness under pressure, or about Candidate D's calmness. Since we already asked about D's calmness and got none, maybe ask Agent1 about Candidate B's teamwork/communication. Also ask Agent3 about Candidate C's calmness under pressure. Also ask about Candidate D's hot temper effect? Already known.\n\nWe need to produce final vote after considering. Likely candidate B has calmness, reliability, good weather assessment, but has weak memory for numbers and makes nasty remarks (bad teamwork). Candidate C has quick correct decisions, conscientious, understands tech, but communication difficulty, egocentric, not willing to further education. Candidate D solves problems well, takes responsibility, but hot temper, know-it-all, maybe not calm. Candidate A anticipates danger, spatial vision, leadership, but show-off, not open to new ideas, no calmness.\n\nLong-distance pilot needs calm under pressure, teamwork, reliability, technical competence, willingness to develop. B has calmness and reliability but teamwork issues and weak numeric memory. C has decision speed, technical, conscientious, but communication and egocentric, not development. D has problem solving, responsibility, but hot temper, know-it-all, unknown calmness. A has anticipation, spatial, leadership, but show-off, not open.\n\nProbably B is strongest in calmness and reliability, but teamwork issues could be mitigated? However, nasty remarks are serious. C's communication issues could be fatal. D's hot temper could be dangerous. A's lack of openness could hinder learning.\n\nThus B might be best despite teamwork flaw. But we might want to ask about B's teamwork to see if it's severe. Let's ask Agent1: \"Do you have information on Candidate B's teamwork or communication style?\" Also ask Agent3: \"Do you have information on Candidate C's calmness under pressure?\" Also maybe ask Agent1 about Candidate D's calmness again? Already no info.\n\nProceed."}
